resources dwindling here on Earth. Powerful international and commercial interests are driving the race to revisit the Moon, but lunar infrastructures could also open breathtaking vistas onto the cosmos. Silk describes how the colonization of the Moon could usher in a thrilling new age of scientific exploration, and lays out what the next fifty years of lunar science might look like. With lunar telescopes of unprecedented size situated in permanently dark polar craters and on the far side of the Moon, we could finally be poised to answer some of the most profound questions confronting humankind, including whether we are alone in the Universe and what our cosmic origins are.Addressing both the daunting challenges and the immense promise of lunar exploration and exploitation, Back to the Moon reveals how prioritizing science, and in particular lunar astronomy, will enable us to address the deepest cosmic mysteries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aLunar bases. 0aSpace colonies. 0aSpace industrialization. 7aSCIENCE / Space Science.2bisacsh  aAge of the universe.  aAlpha Centauri.  aApollo 15.  aApollo program.  aAsteroid mining.  aAsteroid.  aAstronaut.  aAstronomer.  aAstronomy.  aAtmosphere of Earth.  aBackground radiation.  aBig Bang.  aChronology of the universe.  aColonization of the Moon.  aCosmic background radiation.  aCosmic ray.  aDwarf galaxy.  aEarthrise.  aExoplanet.  aExploration of Mars.  aExploration of the Moon.  aExtraterrestrial life.  aFar side of the Moon.  aFormation and evolution of the Solar System.  aGalaxy rotation curve.  aGeology of the Moon.  aGeostationary orbit.  aGeosynchronous orbit.  aGravitational wave.  aGravity wave.  aGravity.  aImpact event.  aInflation (cosmology).  aInfrastructure.  aInternational Space Stat